{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_chinooksalmon_ver03/data/sn84020662/00414185915/1946010201/0900.xml":{"full_text":"THE NOME NUGGET\nPublished Monday, Wednesday and Friday by The\nNOME PUBLISHING CO.\nNome. Alaska\nTelephone: Main 125 P. O. Box 618\n*1.50 PER MONTH *16.00 A YEAR\nW. A. and EMILY BOUCHER..^.Editors\nEntered as second class matter October 14, \\$43, the postoffice at\nNome, Alaska, under the Act of March 3, 187S\nWednesday, January 2, 1946\nPERSPECTIVE\nThis year of 1946 should be one of marked improve\nment in the return to \u201cnormal\u201d peacetime business with\na boom in sight to exceed any the country has ever\nknown, provided however, that labor strife can be con\ncluded.\nLabor is the only postwar problem standing in the\nway of future progress.\nWith the closing of five years of war the scene is\nshifting back to peacetime domestic industries in which\nthe wage and price muddles and strike threats must be\nsettled before employment and production can attain\ntheir goals.\nA number of infant industries will boom, if given a\nchance. The civilian aviation, both private and commer\ncial, will receive added impetus as labor \u201cpermits\u201d re\nconversion to get under full steam, producing consumer\ngoods, in quantities sufficient for the tremendous de\nmand.\n1946 will be a big political year with parties declaring\nall-out campaigning for 34 governorships, 435 House\njobs, and one-third of the seats in the Senate, and Presi\ndent Truman might possibly take the stump in his own\nbehalf.\nNew taxation laws going into effect should give no\nslight impetus to business activity inasmuch as there\nhas been a six billion reduction for the year.\nObservers state that the trend for women is toward\n\u201cultra-femininity in dress, manners, and home, with the\naccent on fireside activities.\nIn science, there will be many new advances, includ\ning the revamping of atom structures, plastics, synthet\nics and prefabricated homes.\nSmall communities are not immue to prosperity or\nimprovement of conditions in which changes are bound\nto come.\nAlaska communities are looking forward with alarm\nto the outcome of the freight rate hearings, which are\nnow set for June 8, this year in Juncftiu, and at a later\ndate in Washington, D. C.\nNome seems to have a fairly good business outlook\nwith optimistic investors putting in more modern equip\nment, rebuilding stores, improving service, new build\nings. With the majority taking this view, there can be\nlittle doubt that there is a bright year ahead for our\ncommunity. Mining is scheduled to reopen with an im\npetus heretofore unknown.\n1946 should be a busy year.\nHOLLYWOOD TO CHICAGO, 3 IfOURS I\nBefore 1955 all new airplanes, including small pri\nvate airplanes, will be equipped with gas turbine or jet j\nmotors, predicts Hall L. Hibbard, vice president andi\nchief engineer of Lockheed Aircraft Corporation.\nYou will \\>e able to fly from Hollywood to Chicago\nin less than three hours in a jpanT^hme that uses gas,\nturbine engines combined witK jeT^propulsion. On\nlonger trips you may fly a part of the way at heights of\n100 miles above the earth in rocket-propelled airplanes\nwhere speed can be increased greatly since air resist\nance is negligible.\nFor slightly over 40 years airplanes have been coast\ning along at subsonic speeds. Now we have the prospect\nof a gas turbine driving a propeller for \u201cslower\u201d speeds\nor a gas turbine operating a jet propulsion unit giving\nthe higher speed more economically than with recipro\ncating engines, Mr. Hibbard explained.\nAt sonic speeds, around 760 miles an hour, compres\nsibility becomes a major problem, causing violent vi\nf IT TO BB UNTIED\n__\nZMftiuuuiJi\n/JWIHHPwWi\nCONTINUED\nFt&WHG.\nbration and buffeting to every surface of the airplane.\nHowever, Mr. Hibbard and other aeronautical en\ngineers believe that if an airplane could pass into the\nsupersonic speed range, compressibility conditions\nprobably approach normal. Therefore, theoretically,\nthere is no limit to the speeds at which we can fly safe\nly. The two major problems of very high speed flight\nare high fuel consumption, which Mr. Hibbard predict\ned will soon be solved, and ways to provide air crews\nflying at high speeds and at high altitudes with livable\ncabins in the sky.\u2014Robert N. Farr in Science Service.\nMOVIES ARE NOT SO RELAXING\n(Science Digest)\nHollywood may be able to use a new scientific find\ning to predict the box-office success of various pictures.\nAll that would be necessary would be to take the tem\nperatures of preview audiences before and after seeing\nthe film, Dr. N. Kleitman, of the University of Chicago,\nsuggests in the magazine Science.\nBody temperature goes up from one-half to one de\ngree Fahrenheit while attending motion pictures, Dr.\nKleitman has found. The rise is enough to be called\n\u201chighly significant.\u201d\nGoing to the movies is far from being relaxing in the\nphysiological sense, this finding shows. The picture may\ngive \u201cescape from the humdrum reality of existence.\u201d\nHowever, even though the spectator is sititng, presum\nably relaxed in a comfortable seat, for two or more\nhours, the subject matter of the film makes his muscles\ntense to such an extent that his temperature goes up.\nDr. Kleitman became interested in the effect of mo\ntion pictures in the course of a long study on the daily\nbody temperature cycle. He found that after attending a\ntwo- or three-hour motion picture show, the subject\u2019s\ntemperature was higher than usual for that particular\ntime of day.\nA teen-aged girl who went to the movies every two or\nthree weeks over a perior of two years and a young\nlady in her early twenties who was a \u201cmovie addict\u2019\u2019\nand went to 29 shows in two months were then made\nsubjects of a special s^udy.\nThe teen-ager s \u201cmovie\u2019 \u2019temperature ranged between\n99 and 100.15 degrees Fahrenheit. At the same time,\nabout 4 p.m., on non-movie days, it ranged from 97.95\nF. to 99.'{O F. The young lady \u201cmovie addict\u201d went to\nshows mostly in the evening. Her temperature rose\nabout half a degree on movie nights, though when she\nsaw a double feature, her temperature was lower after\nthe second feature than after the first. Either the sec\nond feature was less effective than the first in raising\nthe temperature or the normal fall in temperature late\nin the evening was too strong to be reversed.\nHOLLYWOOD\nSTAR-LITES\ni\nI\n1\nBy CHUCK COCHAR^\n*Jots nff to Abbott rmd foctnilo\n\u2014'\"hi pro ropflv eo>n** to do some\nth in\u00ab\u00bb propf with tt'pir mnnpv\u2014\nnnd that\u2019s news in this town\u2014On\na 2Vfe acre site on the eastside of\nIns Angeles\u2014these comics will\nsnend mo^e than $200 000 on Lou1\nOosfello Jr. Youth foundation\u2014a\nolav center and med:eal clinic will\nI\nbe featured. If we had more of\nthese kind of persons there\nwould not be any delinquency in\nthis country of ours.\nJames Craig was a professional\nfootball player, boxer, oil well\ndriller and sales promotion expert\nbefore he became an actor\nSpring Byington\u2019s weight\u2014123\npounds\u2014is exactly the same as\nwhen she started her stage career\n25 years ago.\nSusan Hayward posed for over'\n4000 publicity pictures while first\nunder contract at Warner Bros.\nStudio\u2014and never appeared in a\nmotion picture Loretta Young\nchose her first name for the screen\nin honor of Colleen Moore\u2019s pa\ntron saint.\nBob Cummings\u2019 full name is\nCharles Clarence Robert Orville\nCummings\u2014the Orville, inciden\ntally, is in honor of Orville WrigK^\nand might account for Bob\u2019s all\nconsuming interest in aviation\nRight now he spends one day a\nweek flying Ralph Bellamy\nhad to produce a Broadway show\nwith himself as the star, in order\nto lift himself from the category\nof a dull, colorless character in\nwhich Hollywood had placed him.\nJoe E. Brown began his career\nat the age of 9 as an acrobat and\nwas billed as \u201cBaby Joe, the Child\nWonder\u201d Martha Tilton, as a\nteen-age swing fan, was once Jpr\nchased out of rehearsal hall by?\nBenny Goodman, who hired her a\nfew years later as a vocalist\nLucille Bremer was once a ballet\ndancer with the Philadelphia Op\nera Company and later a member\nof the famed Radio City Music\nHall Rockettes in New York.\nJ. Carroll Naish made his debut\nas a singer\u2014he was one of a trio\nthat sang before President Wilson\nwhen the latter attended a mili\ntary show in Paris while discuss\ning peace terms at the conclusion\nof the First World War.\nGracie Allen got her stage break^\nat the age of three Charles^\nCoburn is the first and only mem\nber of his family to follow the the\nater as a career\u2014his family have\nbeen musicians for three genera\ntions\u2014his grandfather, Moses Co\nburn, invented a pipe organ in\n1870, which was the forerunner\nof the type in use today\u2014the ac\ntor\u2019s late sister, Emma, coached\nLouise Homer, Metropolitan Op\nera singer.\nAt one time Louis Haywara\nplayed the role of Frederic\nMarch\u2019s father in \u201cAnthony Ad-\u00ab$\nverse\u201d Hoagy Carmichael\u2019s\nsong \u201cStardust,\u201d his greatest com\nposition, scored in one evening,\nI gathered dust on the shelf for over\nthree years before it became a\ngreat success Jon Hall raises\npink grapefruit in Florida\u2014first\ni time I\u2019ve ever heard of it.\nJohn Charles Thomas, a firm\n1 believer in the value of time, does\nnot keep an engagement book, but\nhad trained himself to make a\nmental daily schedule which he\nfollows to the letter Brian\nDonlevy has purchased a home in\nHawaii for vacations.","height":"26384","width":"19368"}}
